ğŸ Python Strings

ğŸ“˜ What is a String?
        A string is a data type used to represent textual data.

Strings are sequences of characters.

They are enclosed using:
Single quotes ' '
Double quotes " "
Triple quotes ''' ''' or """ """

Example:
s1 = 'Hello'
s2 = "World"
s3 = '''Hello
World'''

> âœ… Triple quotes are used for multiline strings or to include line breaks.


ğŸ› ï¸ How to Create Strings

You can create strings using single, double, or triple quotes.

single = 'Hello, world!'
double = "Hello, world!"
multiline = '''Hello,
World!
Welcome'''


ğŸ§  Memory Allocation in Strings
        Each character in a string occupies a memory location.

Example:
str = 'PYTHON'
# P | Y | T | H | O | N


ğŸ”¢ String Indexing
        Strings are ordered sequences.
Python uses zero-based indexing.
Negative indexing is also supported.

str = 'PYTHON'
#  P  Y  T  H  O  N
#  0  1  2  3  4  5
# -6 -5 -4 -3 -2 -1

Example:
print(str[2])    # T
print(str[-3])   # H


âœ‚ï¸ String Slicing

Syntax:
string[start : stop : step]

start â†’ starting index
stop â†’ ending index (excluded)
step â†’ increment / skip

Example:
s = 'hello_world'
print(s[1])      # e
print(s[1:3])    # el
print(s[:3])     # hel
print(s[2:])     # llo_world
print(s[::2])    # hlool
print(s[9:2:-2]) # lo_l


ğŸ”’ Mutable vs Immutable

Mutable: Can be changed after creation

Immutable: Cannot be changed after creation


> âš ï¸ " Python strings are immutable "


ğŸ§° Built-in String Methods

ğŸ”¤ Case Conversion Methods

1. capitalize()
      Converts first character to uppercase.

Example:
t = 'inDIA cHINa'
print(t.capitalize())
# India china

2.title()
    Capitalizes first letter of each word.

Example:
print(t.title())
# India China

3.lower()
    Converts string to lowercase.

Example:
print(t.lower())
# india china

4.upper()
    Converts string to uppercase.

Example:
print(t.upper())
# INDIA CHINA

âœ… Boolean Check Methods

f = 'data SCIENCE'
5.print(f.isupper())          # False
6.print(f.islower())          # False
7.print('Python'.isalpha())   # True
8.print('123'.isnumeric())    # True
9.print('abc123'.isalnum())   # True


ğŸ” Search & Replace Methods
      startswith() / endswith()

Example:
f = 'data science'
10.print(f.startswith('d'))
11.print(f.endswith('e'))

12.replace()
Example:
f = 'data'
print(f.replace('a', 'p'))  # dptp


ğŸ”¢ Counting & Indexing

13.count()

Example:
a = 'data science'
print(a.count('e'))  # 2

14.index()
      Returns index of first occurrence.


ğŸ”— Membership Operator
 15.         Checks if substring exists.

Example:
f = 'i love programming language'
print('love' in f)   # True


ğŸ”  ASCII Functions

16.ord()
  Returns ASCII value.
Example:
print(ord('D'))  # 68

17.chr()
    Returns character from ASCII value.
Example:
print(chr(65))  # A


ğŸ”ª Split & Join

18.split()
      Splits string into a list.
Example:
a = 'india is a good country'
b = a.split()
print(b)

19.join()
      Joins elements into a string.
Example:
a = ['india', 'usa', 'uk']
print('->'.join(a))
# india->usa->uk


